1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,055
To understand dirty data,

2
00:00:02,055 --> 00:00:04,800
let's consider the idea of data-driven farming,

3
00:00:04,800 --> 00:00:08,190
which ultimately helps the agricultural value chain.

4
00:00:08,190 --> 00:00:12,660
Suppose we're gathering GPS data on crop yields at the beginning of a quarter,

5
00:00:12,660 --> 00:00:15,360
this data is then going to be used to forecast

6
00:00:15,360 --> 00:00:18,210
the equipments and resources needed for the quarter.

7
00:00:18,210 --> 00:00:20,910
However, due to atmospheric interference,

8
00:00:20,910 --> 00:00:23,340
the GPS data is inaccurate.

9
00:00:23,340 --> 00:00:27,225
Without identifying this data issue and assessing its impact on the data,

10
00:00:27,225 --> 00:00:32,265
we will make incorrect forecasts from the inaccurate data leading to losses.

11
00:00:32,265 --> 00:00:36,630
Inaccurate data represents just one example of a data quality issue.

12
00:00:36,630 --> 00:00:41,850
Low data quality or dirty data hinders data from being used for its intended purposes.

13
00:00:41,850 --> 00:00:44,750
Ensuring high data quality is crucial for obtaining

14
00:00:44,750 --> 00:00:48,230
reliable insights and driving informed decision-making.

15
00:00:48,230 --> 00:00:51,700
Let's draw the same example to talk about messy data.

16
00:00:51,700 --> 00:00:55,760
Our data gathering device is gathering GPS and geospacial data.

17
00:00:55,760 --> 00:00:57,275
But when it stores this data,

18
00:00:57,275 --> 00:01:00,575
it just jumbles all the information into one long line.

19
00:01:00,575 --> 00:01:02,105
Here we have the latitude,

20
00:01:02,105 --> 00:01:04,850
longitude, and date data all at once.

21
00:01:04,850 --> 00:01:07,520
If we had 100 of different records

22
00:01:07,520 --> 00:01:10,100
of this kind of data and just wanted to look at the dates.

23
00:01:10,100 --> 00:01:12,860
It could be really hard to apply any kind of code to

24
00:01:12,860 --> 00:01:16,130
this data because all the information is in one line.

25
00:01:16,130 --> 00:01:20,540
A better way to organize this data is adapting it to a tabular format.

26
00:01:20,540 --> 00:01:23,405
I could then have my latitude, longitude,

27
00:01:23,405 --> 00:01:27,725
and date be individual columns and then focus only on the date column,

28
00:01:27,725 --> 00:01:30,080
like performing additional assessment and cleaning

29
00:01:30,080 --> 00:01:33,400
without having to deal with latitude and longitude.

30
00:01:33,400 --> 00:01:35,110
Messy data, ie,

31
00:01:35,110 --> 00:01:39,755
data with bad structure can be a roadblock for initial data inspection and assessment.

32
00:01:39,755 --> 00:01:43,130
It's important to adapt and fix messy data into a structure

33
00:01:43,130 --> 00:01:46,655
that your tools are compatible with so that the rest of the assessment;

34
00:01:46,655 --> 00:01:50,820
cleaning and using of the data is much easier for you.

